First note that if $N \equiv 0 \pmod{10} $ then $M$ can be equal $\tfrac{1}{10}N $ giving $$\frac{M}{N} = \frac{1}{10} $$ Otherwise we can let $N=\overline{A}0\overline{B} $ where $A$ and $B$ are the positive integers to the left and right of the $0$ that is removed and $B$ has $k$ digits Then it follows that $$\frac{M}{N} = \frac{10^kA+B}{10^{k+1}A+B} $$ We have 
 \begin{align*}
\frac{10^kA+B}{10^{k+1}A+B} &> \frac{10^kA+\tfrac{B}{10}}{10^{k+1}A+B} \\
&= \frac{1}{10} \end{align*} so $\tfrac{1}{10}$ is indeed the minimum Then for the maximum note that 
 \begin{align*}
\frac{10^kA+B}{10^{k+1}A+B} &= \frac{1}{10} + \frac{\tfrac{9B}{10}}{10^{k+1}A+B} \\
&= \frac{1}{10} + \frac{9}{10^{k+2}\tfrac{A}{B}+10} \end{align*} In order to maximize this we wish to minimize $\tfrac{A}{B} $ which clearly occurs at $A=1 B=10^k 1 $ In this case we have 
 \begin{align*}
10^{k+2}\frac{A}{B} &= 10^{k+2} \cdot \frac{1}{10^k 1} \\
&= \frac{10^{k+2}}{10^k 1} \end{align*} which approaches $100$ as $k$ approaches infinity but it is always less than $100 $ Hence the (unattainable) upper bound for $\tfrac{M}{N}$ is 
 \begin{align*}
\frac{1}{10} + \frac{9}{100+10} &= \frac{1}{10} + \frac{9}{110} \\
&= \frac{2}{11} \end{align*} Therefore the smallest interval containing all possible values of $\tfrac{M}{N}$ is $$\left[\frac{1}{10} \frac{2}{11}\right) $$ implying that the answer is $$1000+1000+20+11=\boxed{2031} $$ $\square$

