 \end{bmatrix}\] whence it is clear $\limits_{n \rightarrow \infty}{\frac{x_n}{y_n}} = \frac{3}{2}$

Let $X_n$ be a random variable with value 1 if a point with $n$ neighbors is in the expansion of $C$ and 0 otherwise A point is not in the expansion if neither the point nor its neighbors are in $C$ so $E[X_n] = 1 (1 \frac{1}{2})^{n+1} = 1 \frac{1}{2^{n+1}}$ There are three types of points there are 4 corners with 2 neighbors each there are $98 \cdot 4$ edge points with 3 neighbors each and there are $98^2$ central points with 4 neighbors each By linearity of expectation the expected size of the expansion is 

 \begin{align*}
 &98^2 \cdot E[X_4] + 98 \cdot 4 \cdot E[X_3] + 4 \cdot E[X_2] \\
 &= 98^2 \cdot \frac{31}{32} + 98 \cdot 4 \cdot \frac{15}{16} + 4 \cdot \frac{7}{8} \\
 &= \frac{77399}{8}
\end{align*} 
 The answer is $77399 + 8 = \fbox{77407}$ $\square$

Notice through the sum of sines we obtain \[ 3\sin\left(\tfrac{3x}{2}\right)+3\sin\left(\tfrac{5x}{2}\right) = 6\sin(2x)\cos\left(\tfrac{x}{2}\right) = 12\sin(x)\cos(x)\cos\left(\tfrac{x}{2}\right) \] Substituting yields \begin{align*}
2\sin(x)+2\sin(x)\cos(x)+12\sin(x)\cos(x)\cos\left(\tfrac{x}{2}\right)&=0 \\
1+\cos(x)+6\cos(x)\cos\left(\tfrac{x}{2}\right)&=0 \\
\cos\left(\tfrac{x}{2}\right)&= \tfrac{\cos(x)+1}{6\cos(x)} \\
\end{align*} But by half angle $\cos^2\left(\tfrac{x}{2}\right) = \tfrac{\cos(x)+1}{2}$ Thus we can equate these two results \begin{align*}
\cos^2\left(\tfrac{x}{2}\right) = \tfrac{\cos(x)+1}{2} = \left( \tfrac{\cos(x)+1}{6\cos(x)}\right)^2 \quad \longrightarrow \quad 18\cos^2(x) \cos(x) 1 = 0 \end{align*} Quadratic formula yields $\cos(x) = \tfrac{1 \sqrt{73}}{36}$ which yields $1 + 73 + 36 = \boxed{110}$

Let us define a back step as a step that is in the opposite direction as the previous step (the first step cannot be a back step) Clearly the condition that Connor never encounters his toxic waste is equivalent to him never taking any back steps (because once he has taken two steps from a location which don't cancel each other out he will not encounter his waste if he goes back to that location) We split into two cases when Connor's first four steps are the same and when Connor's first four steps are not all the same Connor's first four steps are the same The probability that Connor's first four steps are all the same as his first one is $(\tfrac{1}{4})^3=\tfrac{1}{64}$ and then the probability that he doesn't take a back step on his fifth step is $\tfrac{2}{3} $ so the total probability for this case is 
 \begin{align*}
\frac{1}{64} \cdot \frac{2}{3} &= \frac{1}{96} \end{align*} 
 Connor's first four steps are not all the same The probability that Connor's first four steps do not contain any backsteps is $(\tfrac{3}{4})^3=\tfrac{27}{64} $ but we must subtract off $\tfrac{1}{64}$ because his first four steps cannot be all the same which gives $\tfrac{26}{64}=\tfrac{13}{32} $ Then the probability that his fifth step is not a back step is $\tfrac{3}{4} $ so the total probability for this case is $$\frac{13}{32} \cdot \frac{3}{4} = \frac{39}{128} $$ 
 Hence adding up the two total probabilities yields 
 \begin{align*}
\frac{1}{96} + \frac{39}{128}
&= \frac{4}{384} + \frac{117}{384} \\
&= \frac{121}{384} \end{align*} so the answer is $$121+384=\boxed{505} $$ $\square$

